{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01YQmpdF9EcpNhCuRN6brnLJ","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I see the key insight. In the `services.yaml`:\n- `es-http` service selects `app: es-cluster` (not `app: elasticsearch`)\n- `es-cluster` headless service selects `app: es-cluster`\n\nBut what's actually deployed in the cluster is different:\n- The existing `es-http` service (already applied) has `selector: app=elasticsearch` (the main cluster)\n- The services from `services.yaml` were supposed to create a NEW `es-http` service pointing to `es-cluster`\n- The transform was meant to run in the no-TLS `es-cluster` and serve through that `es-http` endpoint\n- The `es-transform` nodes function as ingest nodes within `es-cluster`\n\nThe real issue is that `services.yaml` was never actually applied—it got overridden by the pre-existing `es-http` service from stage 01, so the routing still points to the original `elasticsearch` cluster instead of the new one.\n\nLooking at the precondition logs, I can see that only `statefulset.yaml` was applied, which created both `es-cluster` and `es-transform` StatefulSets. But `configmap.yaml` and `services.yaml` were never applied, which explains why the `es-transform-config` ConfigMap is missing and the `es-http` service still routes to the wrong cluster.\n\nThe real issue is that `es-cluster` pods are referencing an `es-config` ConfigMap that doesn't exist—only `elasticsearch-config` is present—so those pods are stuck in `ContainerCreating`. Let me dig into the actual pod status to confirm what's happening.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1298,"cache_read_input_tokens":43864,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1298},"output_tokens":39,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_